24:13.000 --> 24:15.700
we discussed Farmer's penchant for writing under pseudonyms.

24:15.820 --> 24:16.880
As it turns out,

24:16.940 --> 24:19.160
this practice has a very desirable side effect.

24:20.280 --> 24:28.980
One of the funny things about this is that I found out that I could use the fictional author device to break a writing block.

24:29.360 --> 24:31.560
I had a writing block once,

24:31.660 --> 24:35.580
that terrible thing that sometimes happens to writers.

24:36.800 --> 24:38.460
They don't know what causes it.

24:38.640 --> 24:39.580
For some reason,

24:40.210 --> 24:41.480
they might have many ideas,

24:41.580 --> 24:42.380
be eager to go,

24:42.540 --> 24:44.280
but when they sit down in front of a typewriter,

24:44.420 --> 24:44.980
nothing happens.

24:46.420 --> 24:46.920
Well,

24:47.200 --> 24:48.740
that happened to me once.

24:49.580 --> 24:50.940
I never thought it would.

24:51.040 --> 24:52.460
I thought I was immune to such a thing.

24:52.740 --> 24:53.580
But it did.

24:54.540 --> 24:57.480
And after wrestling for two months and getting no place,

24:58.140 --> 24:59.160
I had an idea.

25:00.640 --> 25:03.640
I sat down with the typewriter and wrote a story,

25:05.360 --> 25:07.900
not by Philip Jose Farmer,

25:08.100 --> 25:10.300
but by David Copperfield,

25:10.400 --> 25:10.780
they'd say.

25:11.580 --> 25:13.040
I don't remember which particular nom,

25:13.080 --> 25:13.640
the clue maybe.

25:14.200 --> 25:14.840
Uh,

25:16.180 --> 25:17.340
story poured out.

25:18.860 --> 25:19.800
Very good.

25:20.140 --> 25:20.400
Um,

25:20.800 --> 25:21.580
I thought so anyway.

25:22.740 --> 25:23.060
Uh,

25:23.420 --> 25:24.420
when I'd completed that,

25:24.540 --> 25:26.120
the writing block was gone.

25:26.120 --> 25:26.760
See,

25:26.920 --> 25:28.820
I wasn't writing then as me,

25:29.980 --> 25:30.900
Philip Jose Farmer,

25:31.000 --> 25:31.400
but as,

25:31.680 --> 25:32.320
Kilgore Trout.

25:33.480 --> 25:33.920
And,

25:33.920 --> 25:35.260
I was in his shoes.

25:35.440 --> 25:36.140
I had no trouble.

25:36.420 --> 25:36.780
Now,

25:36.980 --> 25:38.240
the funny thing about this is,

25:38.340 --> 25:38.760
it's a,

25:38.820 --> 25:38.980
uh,

25:40.540 --> 25:41.020
it's a

25:42.060 --> 25:42.940
psychological trick

25:42.940 --> 25:44.340
that I'm conscious of,

25:44.440 --> 25:44.640
see.

25:46.120 --> 25:46.560
Uh,

25:47.580 --> 25:48.440
and yet it works.

25:50.260 --> 25:52.600
It's not like I'm trying to trick my unconscious,

25:52.840 --> 25:53.940
but I must be doing it,

25:54.140 --> 25:54.860
one way or another.

25:57.240 --> 25:57.860
Well,

25:58.180 --> 25:58.520
I don't,

25:58.520 --> 25:59.680
I don't know of anybody else

25:59.680 --> 26:01.700
who's ever broken a writer's block

26:01.700 --> 26:02.420
in that manner,

26:02.580 --> 26:03.880
but I recommend trying it.

26:05.280 --> 26:07.480
Farmer has also written several books

26:07.480 --> 26:08.520
featuring Tarzan

26:08.520 --> 26:09.960
or Tarzan-like characters.

26:10.320 --> 26:11.360
Tarzan Alive

26:11.360 --> 26:12.560
is Tarzan's biography.

26:12.920 --> 26:14.060
The erotic novel,

26:14.140 --> 26:14.900
A Feast Unknown,

26:15.180 --> 26:16.420
and its clean sequels,

26:16.500 --> 26:17.380
The Mad Goblin

26:17.380 --> 26:18.480
and Lord of the Trees,

26:18.680 --> 26:20.360
feature thinly veiled versions

26:20.360 --> 26:21.900
of Tarzan and Doc Savage,

26:22.220 --> 26:23.020
Lord Tiger,

26:23.020 --> 26:24.400
The Opar Books,

26:24.500 --> 26:26.400
and The Adventures of the Peerless Peer

26:26.400 --> 26:28.500
also have Tarzan-like protagonists.

26:28.760 --> 26:29.840
We asked Farmer

26:29.840 --> 26:30.480
when he developed

26:30.480 --> 26:31.760
his interest in Tarzan.

26:32.580 --> 26:34.020
I first read Tarzan

26:34.020 --> 26:35.120
when I guess I was about

26:35.120 --> 26:36.220
seven or eight years old

26:36.220 --> 26:36.880
and I became

26:37.760 --> 26:39.580
wrapped up in that early age

26:39.580 --> 26:41.140
with the works of

26:41.140 --> 26:42.760
Edgar Rice Burroughs.

26:44.800 --> 26:45.320
And,

26:45.860 --> 26:47.740
but when I started college,

26:47.940 --> 26:49.640
I kind of lost interest

26:49.640 --> 26:50.740
and didn't read them anymore.

26:56.500 --> 26:57.280
But later,

26:57.420 --> 26:58.860
Farmer picked up on Tarzan again.

26:58.860 --> 27:00.500
This time he saw Tarzan

27:00.500 --> 27:01.300
in a different light.

27:02.400 --> 27:04.360
I started reading books

27:04.360 --> 27:05.460
about Tarzan again

27:05.460 --> 27:06.700
and this time,

27:07.900 --> 27:09.420
although I still kept

27:10.960 --> 27:15.360
a lot of my childhood interest in him,

27:15.580 --> 27:17.080
a sense of wonder about him,

27:17.260 --> 27:18.900
I began seeing things

27:18.900 --> 27:20.580
in Tarzan, for instance,

27:20.720 --> 27:21.900
I had not seen before.

27:23.260 --> 27:24.200
He was not,

27:24.200 --> 27:27.020
not just a child

27:27.020 --> 27:28.740
who'd been cast away

27:28.740 --> 27:30.840
and raised by great apes

27:30.840 --> 27:32.460
and then become a creature

27:32.460 --> 27:33.000
of the jungle

27:33.000 --> 27:34.200
and then return

27:34.200 --> 27:35.120
to claim fortune.

27:35.140 --> 27:36.280
He was sort of a,

27:37.280 --> 27:38.520
an archetype

27:40.200 --> 27:41.780
of many, many

27:43.140 --> 27:45.120
heroes from classical myths.

27:45.920 --> 27:46.560
And now,

27:46.840 --> 27:47.900
I'm sure that when Burroughs

27:47.900 --> 27:48.320
wrote this,

27:48.400 --> 27:49.020
he didn't know

27:49.020 --> 27:49.560
what he was doing

27:49.560 --> 27:50.940
but he did it unconsciously.

27:51.260 --> 27:52.120
I think that

27:52.120 --> 27:53.080
it's the creation

27:53.080 --> 27:53.680
of Tarzan

27:53.680 --> 27:54.560
and the stroke of genius.

27:55.600 --> 27:56.940
Burroughs is not a great writer

27:56.940 --> 27:57.560
but he has,

27:58.160 --> 27:59.540
he has a great character

27:59.540 --> 28:00.080
just like

28:00.760 --> 28:01.740
A. Conan Doyle

28:01.740 --> 28:03.020
is not a great writer

28:03.020 --> 28:04.100
but he created

28:04.100 --> 28:05.980
a great character.

28:06.280 --> 28:06.940
Sherlock Holmes.

28:07.680 --> 28:09.240
Philip Jose Farmer,

28:09.300 --> 28:10.720
an author with a seemingly

28:10.720 --> 28:11.680
endless supply

28:11.680 --> 28:12.740
of unique ideas

28:12.740 --> 28:14.020
who appears just now

28:14.020 --> 28:14.620
to be gaining

28:14.620 --> 28:15.900
widespread acceptance.

